   Greenhouse gases include a diverse variety of atmospheric gases, as shown in Figure 14. Carbon
   dioxide is a product of burning fossil fuel and wood. Nitrous oxide (NO[2]), produced by
   fertilizer use and released from decomposition of animal wastes is another prominent greenhouse
   gas. Methane (CH[4]) is produced by bacteria (especially in animal intestines), sediments,
   swamps, certain types of landfills, and in flooded rice paddies. In some cases methane can be
   collected and used to generate a small amount of electricity. Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), in
   particular Freon (a refrigerant) are greenhouse gases thought responsible to depletion of the
   planetary ozone layer in the upper atmosphere. Halons, such as halocarbons; C[x]F[x]Br[x]), are
   released from fire extinguishers. Water vapor is a greenhouse gas since clouds reradiate heat
   back to Earth.

